   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": ["If we have a feature $x_i$ with constant value, then Naive Bayes will suffer from dividing by zero when it tries to fit a Gaussian distribution for $x_i$ since the variance of $x_i$ is zero. In Sklearn GaussianNB, this issue is avoided by using a parameter \textbf{var\_smoothing}, which is the portion of the largest variance of all features that is added to variances for calculation stability. If \textbf{var\_smoothing} is too large, the fitted Naive Bayes model will suffer from under-fitting because large variances lead to a simple model."]
  }
